Made this last night for a dinner party of six. Everyone loved the pork - including my fussy husband who doesn't like cooked fruit. The fennel, mustard combination was excellent. From room temperature, it took about 25 minutes to hit 150F (a PERFECT temperature - after sitting, the meat was just slightly pink) so adjust your schedule. I prepped the meat and apple mixture several hours ahead. Tripled the amount of meat for six; doubled the apple mixture. Doubling the meat might have been pretty close to enough. Cut the apples in larger chunks and added to the meat half way through the cooking process - worked well to keep mixture from mushing up. The mixture seemed too chunky however for the sliced tenderloin. Next time, I will cut the apples and onions into a large dice and add dried cranberries (the sliced onion produced wimpy rings). I'll make it ahead of time, brown it ahead of time, and add to roaster after 15 minutes. The fennel seeds on the pork seemed a little coarse to me. I liked the amount of flavor, but not the amount of seeds floating around. Next time, I'll whiz quickly in the food processor and then mix with the mustard (which I'll increase amount of if necessary) and then rub onto the tenderloins. Don't let my ramblings put you off - this is a terrific recipe that I'll definitely make again. I'm hoping that my changes will make it a Four Fork entree the next time.

