Rating: 4
Overall, I thought this was an excellent recipe. I would echo other reviewers who thought 14 oz. of tenderloin was not enough for four servings - I made two tenderloins weighing a total of 2.25 pounds. I didn't increase the amount of fennel and am glad, since the 2 tsps. seemed like plenty, even with more meat. I also increased the cooking time by about eight minutes and it was just right - the tenderloins were juicy but not pink. I didn't have the whole-grain dijon so used plain - it was fine, but I'd still like to try it with the whole-grain dijon. Since so many complained of the mushy texture of the apple/onion mix, I didn't saute the apples in advance. Instead, I sliced them a little thicker than the recipe called for and put them in during the last five minutes of roasting. They kept their shape and some of their texture and browned up nicely during the reduction process. My husband, who is normally leery of these kinds of combinations, loved the reduction and ate every bite.

